He lived for many years contented with one wife, never frequented drinking-parties, except to consult upon war, and was a, bitter enemy to drunkenness and drunkards. Though formerly the prince of plundererS, he was now become a severe avenger of plunderings. He was as well ac— quainted with the ordinances of religion as with his own name. He shunned no labour conducive to his own advantage or that of the town, and was assiduous in cultivating land and breeding cattle. He might, therefore, have been initiated into the Roman Catholic re- ligion long before, and indeed he frequently as- sured us of his intention to be SO, as soon as ever his mind was free from anxiety respecting his rival Oaherkaikin. In fact, when the Vice- Governor Francisco de Vera Muxica was in the town of St. Jeronymo, he requested bap— tism of his own accord, but was desired by the same to wait a little, because he wished to per- form the ceremony in the city of Sta. Fe, with great magnificence.
